      <title>Worksheet for Sections 5.1â€“5.4</title>

      <introduction>
        <p>
          These exercises are designed to help you practice the concepts of the definite integral and the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise workspace="2in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Which of the following are equal to
            <me>
              \int_1^5 \frac{\ln x}{x} \, dx
            </me>
            ?
          </p>
        </statement>


        <choices>
          <choice correct="no">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\sum_{i = 1}^5 \frac{\ln x_i}{x_i} \Delta x</m>, where <m>\Delta x = 4/n</m> and <m>x_i = 1 + i \Delta x_i</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                This is <m>R_5</m> approximating <m>\int_1^5 \frac{\ln x}{x} \, dx</m>
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>

          <choice correct="no">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\lim_{n \to \infty} \sum_{i = 1}^5 \frac{\ln x_i}{x_i} \Delta x</m>, where <m>\Delta x = 4/n</m> and <m>x_i = 1 + i \Delta x_i</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                The sum counts only the first five terms in <m>R_n</m>.
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>

          <choice correct="yes">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \lim_{n \to \infty} \sum_{i = 1}^n \frac{\ln x_i}{x_i} \Delta x</m>, where <m>\Delta x = 4/n</m> and <m>x_i = 1 + i \Delta x_i</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                Yes, this is <m>\lim_{n\to\infty} R_n</m>, which converges to <m>\int_1^5 \frac{\ln x}{x}\,dx</m>.
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>

          <choice correct="yes">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(\ln 5)^2/2</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                Yes.
                <m>\frac{d}{dx}\frac{1}{2}\left(\ln x\right)^2 = \ln(x) \cdot \frac{1}{x}</m>, so
                <me>
                  \begin{aligned} \int_1^5 \int_1^5 \frac{\ln x}{x}\,dx &amp;= \left.\frac{1}{2}\left(\ln x\right)^2\right|^5_1 \\ &amp;= \frac{1}{2}\left(\ln 5\right)^2 - \frac{1}{2}\left(\ln 1\right)^2 \\ &amp;= \frac{1}{2}\left(\ln 5\right)^2 \end{aligned}
                </me>
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>

          <choice correct="no">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{5^2} - \frac{1}{1^2}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                No, this is not correct.
                You may be using <m>\frac{1}{x^2}</m> as an antiderivative of <m>\frac{\ln x}{x}</m>, which it is not.
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>

          <choice correct="no">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \frac{\ln 1}{1} + \frac{\ln 2}{2} + \frac{\ln 3}{3} + \frac{\ln 4}{4}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                No, this is not correct.
                This is the sum of the first four terms in <m> R_n</m>, which approximates <m>\int_1^5 \frac{\ln x}{x} \, dx</m>.
                The correct answer is the limit of <m>R_n</m> as <m>n\to\infty</m>.
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>
        </choices>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <p>
          Put the following in <term>ascending</term> order (with <q> <m>=</m> </q> or <q> <m>&lt;</m> </q> signs between each expression.
          You do not need to justify your solution.
          [<em>Hint</em>: Think about which expressions are positive, which are negative, and which are zero.
          A picture may be helpful.]
        </p>

        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \int_2^6 \ln t \, dt</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ln 2 + \ln 3 + \ln 4 + \ln 5</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ln 3 + \ln 4 + \ln 5 + \ln 6</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                zero
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\ln(2/6)</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\ln(2 + h) - \ln 2}{h}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </exercise>
